              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Counter Strategies to Dark Side Senate: An In Depth Look</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2808"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2808"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=543">James "Eclypse" Valeri</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 543 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A short and sweet look at ways of dealing with Dark Senate without completely altering your deck.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">It seems that Dark Side senate decks are the latest rage in the SWCCG community. I&#146;m sure you&#146;ve often heard the phrase &quot;you can&#146;t touch the senate.&quot; Well, that just isn&#146;t true. There are plenty of ways to deal with this annoying menace, and certainly one of them should fit into your deck seemlessly. This article does not claim to be the authority on anything, mind you. Merely a look at possible couter-strategies against a current popular one. Let&#146;s take a look.<br>
<br>
1. Force Choke: Some Dark Senate decks don&#146;t activate a whole lot, at least not in the early game. This is a good thing, because this deck&#146;s mechanics can get expensive. Once flipped, it costs the dark player 3 force each turn to place 2 cards from your hand in the used pile. Now, couple that with Battle Plan. In order for them to drain and take those cards, they have to pay 3 for each, and they take another card from their force pile with Lot Dodd. Most dark senate decks don&#146;t pack a lot of space power either, so this effect can limit the options placed before the Dark player and buy you some time. Other force choke methods, such as Watch Your Step, Revolution, Obi-Wan&#146;s Apparition, and Aim High may also be effective in choking the life force from the senate.<br>
<br>
2. New Leadership is Needed: Take a look in your deck...go ahead look inside. You might just find a character with politics in there. All you need is a Rebel leader with ability&lt;4, and whahlah! Instant politics! So what? Well, with New Leadership, just plop that character to the senate and send whatever senator you don&#146;t like into the used pile. If you send Lot Dodd to the used pile (and you&#146;ve cancelled the Phantom Menace) it could take the Dark player a couple of turns to get that character back to the senate to make a difference. Taking out Lot Dodd can be crippling to this deck. Taking out Edcel can give you that game winning battle. Taking out Tikkes can increase the Force Choke. You get the idea. Examples of commonly used Rebel Leaders are Wedge (WYS, HB), Han, Madine (RST), Calrissian and Ackbar (QMC). Some of these can be repulled later with Balanced Attack, Strike Planning or Squadron Assignments.<br>
<br>
3. Multiple Destinies: Remember the days of old when you dropped a ton of characters to a site and drew a ton of battle destiny with adding interrupts? Those days are back! Track some high destiny, drop some mains down to the senate, play those interrupts and clear it out. Sure you get no power and permanent weapons, but high destiny is enough to clear out the senate and set back the opponent for a few turns, possibly for the rest of the game. You can do this without any resistance really, because Edcel Bar Gane&#146;s text only works at battleground sites, and Guri&#146;s text would be cancelled. So really, you can draw as much destiny as you like. If you wanna shoot a non-permanent gun, incidentally, a tracked 6 or 7 and Blaster Proficiency can work wonders in taking out key senatorial figures  =^)<br>
<br>
4. Blast the Door Kid!: Your opponent won&#146;t see this one coming. This one I would actually suggest for the Light Senate deck, simply because Light has more lower ability characters with politics than Dark. In fact, most of Dark&#146;s senators are ability &gt;2. This can set up for a serious beatdown in the Senate, excluding most, if not all but one senator from battle. This can easily be achieved with WYS or a Light Senate deck, of if you play Jedi Pack Han, Chewie and Life Debt (good for Hyperdrive Generator Objective). Couple this with I&#146;ve got a Bad Feeling About This to double or triple the damage.<br>
<br>
5. Ya can&#146;t beat &#146;em, join &#146;em!: It is possible for Light Senate to beat Dark Senate, for a couple of reasons. A. Light Side has Bacta Tank, and that allows the Light player to forfiet low deploy, high forfeit senators and use them again later. B. Yarua is beats, because you can reduce characters with wealth agendas right in the middle of a battle, possibly giving you a majority and all the benefits therein. C. You can play Blast The Door Kid! to cause serious overflow damage. If they chose not to delpy those senators, well, that&#146;s 3 less characters Dark can play with. D. If they wanna reduce Valorum&#146;s politics, that costs force, which if you impliment a force choke, shouldn&#146;t be a problem. If they don&#146;t have the force, they can&#146;t reduce him. In my experience, this deck has the tools needed to beat dark senate - you just have to utilize them.<br>
<br>
Dark Side Senate is powerful yes...but not unbeatable. I hope this article has shown you some effective methods in dealing with a popular decktype. The senate is tricky, and the rules really aren&#146;t the same there at all. But therein lies the secret to beating it. In future articles I hope to go in depth on Podracing, WYS, and other strategies. Until then, God bless. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2808"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2808"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2808" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <!-- #EndEditable --></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
